## Data Science Kelleher

Chapter 1 & 2

Data science is about improving decision making by insights extracted from large data sets.

Data science includes a set of principals, problems definitions, algorithms, and processes for extracting non-obvious and useful patterns from large data sets.

Data science includes ML and data mining, and also includes stuff like capturing, leaning and transforming data.

Data science allows for customer segmentation/clustering.

Or association rule minding, identify products that are brought together.

Or anomaly or outlier detection.

Classification/prediction. - predicting a missing value or attribute, rather than what will happen in the future. e.g. predict if an email is spam.

Data science is for when there is too much data, complexity or logic, that a human couldn't do it.

Insight means a pattern that isn't obvious.

Actionable means something that we can use.

We want actionable insights.

Transactional data includes event information such as the sale of an item, etc.

Relational databases store data as one row per instance and one column per attribute.

Big data is defined in terms of the three Vs, volume of data, variety of data, and velocity it must be processed.

Resulted in the development of NoSQL databases - simplier data models than traditional relational databases.

NoSQL stores data as JSON, so as an object representation.

Big data is also about processing data quickly, e.g. MapReduce in Hadoop. Queries are processed on multiple servers then reduce(merged) together.

Laplace took Bayes and Prices' work and developed them into what we call Bayes' Rule.

Gauss developed the method of least squares. Used for linear regression and logistic regression, as well as artificial network models used in AI.

Playfair invested statistical graphics and laying the foundation for data visualisation and exploratory data analysis. Invested the line chart, area chart for time-series data, bar chart and pie chart.

t-distributed stochastic neighbour embedding(t-SME) algorithm, used to reduce high-dimensional data down to two or three dimensions allowing visualisation.

Pearson developed modern hypothesis testing. Fisher developed statistical method for multivariate analysis and introduced the idea of maximum likelihood estimate into statistical inferance.

Turing in the Second World War led to the invention of the electronic computer.

McCulloch and Pitts proposed the first neural network.

Shannon published A mathematical theory of communication and founded information theory.

Fix and Hodges proposed a model for discriminatory analysis - classification or pattern recognition, the basis of nearest neighbour model.

Nilsson showed how neural networks could learn linear models for classification.

Hunt, Marin and Stone developed concept-learning system framework, a progenitor of decision tree models.

Various people published early version of k-means clustering algorithm.

Two approaches, the ML approach of most accurate prediction, vs models that explain the reasoning why.

Skills of a Data scientist

- Communication
- Domain expertise
- Data ethic and regulations
- Data wrangling and databases
- Computer science and HPC
- Data visualisation
- Statistic & probability
- Machine learning

You might miss outlier on a table, but they will stick out when visualised.

### Chapter 2 what are data and what is the data set?

Data science if dependent on the data.

Variable, feature and attribute are often used interchangeable.

An analytics record is a n*m matric, rows and columns.

Including irrelevent data points, is more work getting in and cleansing the data, and can actually impede models.

Numeric attributes are on interval or ratio scale. Interval is something like date, where difference makes sense but not multiplication. No zero origin.

Ratio has a true zero origin. So like Kelvin but not Celsius

Nominal, are names, e.g. single, married or divorced. There is no arithmetic that can be applied to them

Ordinal attributes are like nominal attributes but can be ordered. e.g. like, neutral, dislike.

Data we use is not a perfect representation of the real world.

Myths

- Data science is just stats. It's more than that it includes, domain knowledge, machine learning, software engineering, visualisation, etc.
- More data means better insights. Quality data is better than just more data. Poor quality data can lead to issues.
- It's only for companies with big data. SME companies can benefit, using SaaS.
- Every data scientist is a machine learning expert. Some specialise in certain areas.
- Data science will replace human decision-making. They can provide powerful insights and automate process, but human oversight is crucial.

DIKW pyramid

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Data: raw data

Information: Data that is processed and structured.

Knowledge: Information that can answer "how".

Wisdom: Ultimate use of knowledge to make practical and ethical decisions.

iXBRL - Data

BDCT - information

Datum is a single piece of data

Attributes/features or variable mean same thing.

A dataset is a nxm matrix, rows and attributes

A dataset must be structured in a way that aligns with the objective of the data analysis project.

Create a dataset

- Collect data
- Data cleaning
- Transformation
- Integration. If from different data sources, i.e. match formats, etc.
- Formatting, SQL, JSON, CSV.

Relationships

- Must involve two entities, although it could be with itself
- Can't be more than two entities

If data needs to be stored about the relationship then it's an entity.

If the relationship can occur multiple times, then they should be stored separately and will also be an entity.

Nouns are entities

Verbs are relationships

A data model describes how data is represented within a system

Conceptual model

Identifies what concepts(entities) the data model is about

Describes how the concepts relate to each other

Logical data model

Identifies what information will be stored about each entity

Labels the relationships

So stuff like data types, key attributes, etc.

Physical data model

Precisely describes how the data will be stored and their types

May introduce additional constraints

Includes selecting a database

Entities become tables

Attributes become columns

Primary and foreign keys specified

How to develop a data model

- Top down from business requirements
- Bottom up, from example data

Data types

Structured like SQL

Semi-structured like XML or JSON

Quasi-structured 0 some organisational structure but doesn't fit neatly into the structure of a relational database. e.g. log files, emails

Unstructured like text, images, videos

Raw data are direct abstractions like weight or height.

Derived data is like a BMI

Captured data are direction measurements,

Exhaust data are biproducts, like metadata.

Attributes are either numerical(continuous or discrete) or categorical(ordinal[e.g. poor to good] or nominal[e.g. colours])

Satisfaction scores (ordinal data) meadia or mode scores

Sales data(numerical data) time series to predict future.

Employee categorisation(categorical data) Analysis may use bar charts to display distribution.

Bias types

Sampling bias, sample isn't representative

Measurement bias, faulty measurement equipment

Confirmation bias, analyst that favour information that confirms the pre-conceptions

Mitigating bias

- Awareness and training
- Diverse data sources
- Robust sampling techniques
- Rigorous data cleaning
- Blind analysis, where analyst don't know the hypothesis or expected outcome

Good data governance ensure data is consistent, trustworthy and isn't misued

An organisation should have a data controller and data processor

Data architecture are the models, policies, rules and standard for how data is collected, stored, integrated and used.

Data analysis is the applying statistical and logical techniques to describe, and evaluate data.

Data governance allows for good data architecture, which allows for good data analysis, which confirms the trustworthiness of the data and validates governance and architecture frameworks.

Cross-Industry Standard Process for Data Mining(CRISP-DM) is a widely adopted data mining process models.
